	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>EP rapporteur highlights her concerns about the EU–Kiribati FPA</h1>

			
			<h4>
												05 August 2013
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>Isabella Lövin, the European Parliament rapporteur for the EU–Kiribati FPA, proposes that parliament should vote against the agreement protocol. She developed her argument in a reply
<a href="http://isabellalovin.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/06/2013-06-25-Reply_to_Kiribati_on_protocol_Final.pdf" target="_blank"> t</a>o the Kiribati’s government letter, asking why Kiribati has agreed to a protocol that is not based on the regionally agreed Vessel Day Scheme (VDS), when “according to the official agreed records of the FPA Joint Committee, Kiribati had actually made it clear at the start of the negotiations that they intended to base the new protocol on the VDS. Moreover, Kiribati implemented the VDS in all bilateral agreements renewed in 2011 including Japan, Taiwan, China and New Zealand.”</p><p>Ms Lövin underlines that EU purse seiners operating in Kiribati are among the largest of their kind, and rely heavily on the use of fish aggregating devices, a factor that may affect their fishing effort. “Therefore it is of the utmost importance that their effort be properly accounted for.”</p><p>She also recalled the EP resolution on the EU external fisheries policy when the European Parliament expressed its wish that bilateral fisheries agreements should ensure that EU shipowners pay a fair and market-based portion of the costs when acquiring access rights.</p><p>Greenpeace made a supporting formal statement in which the NGO highlighted that, if the agreement was not rejected, “the EU will walk away with a bargain price for the opportunity to fish.” The EP Fisheries Committee is due to give its opinion on the deal in October.</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p>Letter from Kiribati Ministry of Fisheries to MEP Isabella Lövin, 10&nbsp;June 2013</p><p>
<a href="http://isabellalovin.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/06/2013-06-10_Ratification_Kiribati_EU_bilateral_agreement_at_the_EU_Parliament.pdf" target="_self">http://isabellalovin.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/06/2013-06-10_Ratificat...</a>&nbsp;</p><p>Letter from MEP Isabella Lövin to Kiribati Ministry of Fisheries, 25&nbsp;June 2013</p><p>
<a href="http://isabellalovin.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/06/2013-06-25-Reply_to_Kiribati_on_protocol_Final.pdf" target="_self">http://isabellalovin.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/06/2013-06-25-Reply_to_...</a></p><p><i>Atuna.com</i>, ‘EU tuna deal with Kiribati should be rejected’, 5&nbsp;July 2013</p><p>
<a href="http://www.atuna.com/apps/public/ViewArticle.asp?ID=13086" target="_self">http://www.atuna.com/aps/public/ViewArticle.asp?ID=13086</a></p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>Two issues – of interest to all ACP coastal countries – are raised in the discussions of the FPA between the EU and Kiribati: a) how to determine a fair price for foreign fleets’ access, and ensure the rent is fairly paid by all; b) how to respect and promote regional agreements and dynamics in a way that reinforces fisheries governance. Determining a fair price should take into account ACP countries’ costs for managing their fisheries, as well as benefits to be expected for local development. An element to be taken into account, which could modulate the price, is whether the catches – or part of them – are landed locally for processing. In the case of Kiribati, it needs to be noted that, in the new protocol, the shipowner's fee was substantially increased. Currently, the FPAs’ protocols generally apply national legislation; it is therefore Kiribati’s responsibility ultimately to decide on how to regulate access to their waters. However, this should not stop the EU and its ACP partners from maintaining a dialogue about how schemes such as VDS could be improved, particularly in terms of transparency and compliance by all foreign fleets with the scheme.</p>
		</div>
		
